---
description: Avoid expression-bodied (arrow =>) implementations for class methods
globs: **/*.cs
alwaysApply: false
---

# No Arrow Functions for Class Methods

Use block bodies for class methods. Expression-bodied members (`=>`) are only acceptable for simple property getters, trivial one-liner lambdas passed as arguments, and operator overloads.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — arrow body on a class method
public override Task HandleEventAsync(IEvent @event, CancellationToken ct)
    => ProcessAsync(@event, ct);

protected ValueTask PublishAsync(IEvent @event, CancellationToken ct)
    => Publisher.PublishAsync(@event, ct);

public Task StartAsync(CancellationToken ct) => Task.CompletedTask;

// ✅ GOOD — block body for class methods
public override Task HandleEventAsync(IEvent @event, CancellationToken ct)
{
    return ProcessAsync(@event, ct);
}

protected ValueTask PublishAsync(IEvent @event, CancellationToken ct)
{
    return Publisher.PublishAsync(@event, ct);
}

public Task StartAsync(CancellationToken ct)
{
    return Task.CompletedTask;
}

// ✅ OK — simple property getters and lambdas
public string Name => _name;
private KafkaListenerOptions Options => _optionsMonitor.Get(Name);
services.AddKeyedSingleton<IComponent>(name, (sp, _) => Create(sp));
```
